Common sign and symptom of short bowel syndrome may include: Diarrhea Greasy, foul-smelling stool Fatigue Weight loss Malnutrition Swelling (edema) in the lower extremity Causes Causes of short bowel syndrome include having part of your small intestine removed during surgery, or being born with some of the small intestine missing or damaged. Conditions that may require surgical removal of portion of the small intestine include Crohn's disease, cancer, injury and blood clots. The sign and symptom of hypopituitarism usually develop gradually and get worse over time. They are sometimes subtle and may be overlooked for month or even years. But for some people, sign and symptom develop suddenly. Signs and symptom of hypopituitarism vary from person to person, depending on which pituitary hormone are affected and to what degree. In people who have more than one pituitary hormone deficiency, the second deficiency may increase or, in some cases, hide the symptom of the first deficiency. Growth hormone (GH) deficiency In children, GH deficiency may cause growth problem and short stature. Most adult who have GH deficiency don't have any symptoms, but for some adult it can cause: GH GH Fatigue Muscle weakness Changes in body fat composition Lack of ambition Social isolation Luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) deficiency Deficiency of these hormones, called gonadotropins, affect the reproductive system. In women, the deficiency decrease egg and estrogen production from the ovaries. In men, the deficiency decrease sperm and testosterone production from the testicles. Women and men may experience a lower sex drive, infertility or fatigue. In child and adolescents, delayed puberty is usually the only symptom. Women may also have symptom such as: Hot flash Irregular or no period Loss of pubic hair An inability to produce milk for breast-feeding Men may also have symptom such as: Erectile dysfunction Decreased facial or body hair Mood change Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) deficiency This hormone control the thyroid gland. A TSH deficiency lead to low level of thyroid hormone (hypothyroidism). This cause symptom such as: TSH Fatigue Weight gain Dry skin Constipation Sensitivity to cold or difficulty staying warm Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) deficiency This hormone help your adrenal gland work properly, and help your body react to stress. Symptoms of ACTH deficiency include: ACTH Severe fatigue Low blood pressure, which may lead to fainting Frequent and prolonged infection Nausea, vomiting or abdominal pain Confusion Anti-diuretic hormone (ADH) deficiency This hormone, which is also called vasopressin, help your body balance it fluid levels. An ADH deficiency can cause a disorder called diabetes insipidus, which can cause: ADH Excessive urination Extreme thirst Electrolyte imbalance Prolactin deficiency Prolactin is the hormone that tell the body when to start making breast milk. Low level of prolactin can cause woman to have problem making milk for breast-feeding.

Multiple sclerosis sign and symptom may differ greatly from person to person and over the course of the disease depending on the location of affected nerve fibers. Common symptom include: Numbness or weakness in one or more limb that typically occurs on one side of your body at a time Tingling Electric-shock sensation that occur with certain neck movements, especially bending the neck forward (Lhermitte sign) Lack of coordination Unsteady gait or inability to walk Partial or complete loss of vision, usually in one eye at a time, often with pain during eye movement Prolonged double vision Blurry vision Vertigo Problems with sexual, bowel and bladder function Fatigue Slurred speech Cognitive problem Mood disturbance

For many people with pectus excavatum, the only sign or symptom is a slight indentation in their chests. In some people, the depth of the indentation worsens in early adolescence and can continue to worsen into adulthood. In severe case of pectus excavatum, the breastbone may compress the lung and heart. Signs and symptom may include: Decreased exercise tolerance Rapid heartbeat or heart palpitation Recurrent respiratory infection Wheezing or coughing Chest pain Heart murmur Fatigue Dizziness

The sign and symptom of pelvic inflammatory disease might be mild and difficult to recognize. Some woman don't have any sign or symptoms. When sign and symptom of PID are present, they most often include: PID Pain — ranging from mild to severe — in your lower abdomen and pelvis Unusual or heavy vaginal discharge that may have an unpleasant odor Unusual bleeding from the vagina, especially during or after sex, or between period Pain during sex Fever, sometimes with chill Painful, frequent or difficult urination

Symptoms of delirium usually begin over a few hour or a few days. They typically occur with a medical problem. Symptoms often come and go during the day. There may be period of no symptoms. Symptoms tend to be worse at night when it's dark and thing look le familiar. They also tend to be worse in setting that aren't familiar, such a in a hospital. Primary symptom include the following. Reduced awareness of surroundings This may result in: Trouble focusing on a topic or changing topic Getting stuck on an idea rather than responding to question Being easily distracted Being withdrawn, with little or no activity or little response to surroundings Poor thinking skill This may appear as: Poor memory, such a forgetting recent event Not knowing where they are or who they are Trouble with speech or recalling word Rambling or nonsense speech Trouble understanding speech Trouble reading or writing Behavior and emotional change These may include: Anxiety, fear or distrust of others Depression A short temper or anger A sense of feeling elated Lack of interest and emotion Quick change in mood Personality change Seeing thing that others don't see Being restless, anxious or combative Calling out, moaning or making other sound Being quiet and withdrawn — especially in older adult Slowed movement or being sluggish Changes in sleep habit A switched night-day sleep-wake cycle Types of delirium Experts have identified three types: Hyperactive delirium. This may be the easiest type to recognize. People with this type may be restless and pace the room. They also may be anxious, have rapid mood swing or see thing that aren't there. People with this type often resist care. Hypoactive delirium. People with this type may be inactive or have reduced activity. They tend to be sluggish or drowsy. They might seem to be in a daze. They don't interact with family or others. Mixed delirium. Symptoms involve both type of delirium. The person may quickly switch back and forth from being restless and sluggish. Delirium and dementia Delirium and dementia may be hard to tell apart, and a person may have both. Someone with dementia ha a gradual decline of memory and other thinking skill due to damage or loss of brain cells. The most common cause of dementia is Alzheimer's disease, which come on slowly over month or years. Delirium often occurs in people with dementia. However, episode of delirium don't always mean a person ha dementia. Tests for dementia shouldn't be done during a delirium episode because the result could be misleading. Some difference between the symptom of delirium and dementia include: Onset. The onset of delirium occurs within a short time — within a day or two. Dementia usually begin with minor symptom that get worse over time. Attention. The ability to stay focused or maintain focus is impaired with delirium. A person in the early stage of dementia remains generally alert. Someone with dementia often isn't sluggish or agitated. Rapid change in symptoms. Delirium symptom can come and go several time during the day. While people with dementia have better and worse time of day, their memory and thinking skill typically stay at a constant level.

Hurthle cell cancer doesn't always cause symptoms, and it's sometimes detected during a physical examination or an imaging test done for some other reason. When they do occur, sign and symptom may include: A lump in the neck, just below the Adam's apple Pain in the neck or throat Hoarseness or other change in your voice Shortness of breath Swallowing difficulty These sign and symptom don't necessarily mean that you have Hurthle cell cancer. They may be indication of other medical condition — such a inflammation of the thyroid gland or an enlargement of the thyroid (goiter).

Your limb have specific area of muscle (compartments). Your lower leg, for example, ha four compartments. Chronic exertional compartment syndrome often occurs in the same compartment of an affected limb on both side of the body, usually the lower leg. Signs and symptom can include: Aching, burning or cramping pain in a compartment of the affected limb Tightness in the affected limb Numbness or tingling in the affected limb Weakness of the affected limb Foot drop, in severe cases, if leg are affected Occasionally, swelling or bulging a a result of a muscle hernia Pain caused by chronic exertional compartment syndrome typically follows this pattern: Begins consistently after a certain time, distance or intensity of exertion after you start exercising the affected limb Progressively worsens a you exercise Becomes le intense or stop completely within 15 minute of stopping the activity Over time, recovery time after exercise may increase Taking a complete break from exercise or performing only low-impact activity might relieve your symptoms, but relief is usually only temporary. Once you take up running again, for instance, those familiar symptom usually come back.

Common childhood asthma sign and symptom include: Frequent coughing that worsens when your child ha a viral infection, occurs while your child is asleep or is triggered by exercise or cold air A whistling or wheezing sound when breathing out Shortness of breath Chest congestion or tightness Childhood asthma might also cause: Trouble sleeping due to shortness of breath, coughing or wheezing Bouts of coughing or wheezing that get worse with a cold or the flu Delayed recovery or bronchitis after a respiratory infection Trouble breathing that hamper play or exercise Fatigue, which can be due to poor sleep Asthma sign and symptom vary from child to child, and might get worse or better over time. Your child might have only one indication, such a a lingering cough or chest congestion. It can be difficult to tell whether your child's symptom are caused by asthma. Periodic or long-lasting wheezing and other asthma-like symptom can be caused by infectious bronchitis or another respiratory problem.

There are three general type of thoracic outlet syndrome: Neurogenic (neurologic) thoracic outlet syndrome. This most common type of thoracic outlet syndrome is characterized by compression of the brachial plexus. The brachial plexus is a network of nerve that come from your spinal cord and control muscle movement and sensation in your shoulder, arm and hand. Venous thoracic outlet syndrome. This type of thoracic outlet syndrome occurs when one or more of the vein under the collarbone (clavicle) are compressed, resulting in blood clots. Arterial thoracic outlet syndrome. This is the least common type of TOS. It occurs when one of the artery under the collarbone is compressed, resulting in bulging of the artery, also known a an aneurysm. It's possible to have a mix of the three different type of thoracic outlet syndrome, with multiple part of the thoracic outlet being compressed. Thoracic outlet syndrome symptom can vary depending on the type. When nerve are compressed, sign and symptom of neurogenic thoracic outlet syndrome include: Numbness or tingling in your arm or finger Pain or ache in your neck, shoulder, arm or hand Weakening grip Signs and symptom of venous thoracic outlet syndrome can include: Discoloration of your hand (bluish color) Arm pain and swelling Blood clot in vein in the upper area of your body Arm fatigue with activity Paleness or abnormal color in one or more finger or your hand Throbbing lump near your collarbone Signs and symptom of arterial thoracic outlet syndrome can include: Cold fingers, hand or arm Hand and arm pain Lack of color (pallor) or bluish discoloration (cyanosis) in one or more of your finger or your entire hand Weak or no pulse in the affected arm

Usually, a split (cleft) in the lip or palate is immediately identifiable at birth. Cleft lip and cleft palate may appear as: A split in the lip and roof of the mouth (palate) that affect one or both side of the face A split in the lip that appears a only a small notch in the lip or extends from the lip through the upper gum and palate into the bottom of the nose A split in the roof of the mouth that doesn't affect the appearance of the face Less commonly, a cleft occurs only in the muscle of the soft palate (submucous cleft palate), which are at the back of the mouth and covered by the mouth's lining. This type of cleft often go unnoticed at birth and may not be diagnosed until later when sign develop. Signs and symptom of submucous cleft palate may include: Difficulty with feeding Difficulty swallowing, with potential for liquid or food to come out the nose Nasal speaking voice Chronic ear infection

A tumor is an abnormal growth or mass of tissue. A cyst is a lesion that contains liquid or semisolid material. Examples of jaw tumor and cyst include: Ameloblastoma. This rare, usually noncancerous (benign) tumor begin in the cell that form the protective enamel lining on the teeth. It develops most often in the jaw near the molars. The most common type is aggressive, forming large tumor and growing into the jawbone. Although this tumor can recur after treatment, aggressive surgical treatment will typically reduce the chance of recurrence. Central giant cell granuloma. Central giant cell granuloma are benign lesion that grow from bone cells. They most often occur in the front portion of the lower jaw. One type of these tumor can grow rapidly, cause pain and destroy bone, and ha a tendency to recur after surgical treatment. The other type is le aggressive and may not have symptoms. Rarely, a tumor may shrink or resolve on it own, but typically these tumor require surgical treatment. Dentigerous cyst. This cyst originates from tissue that surround a tooth before it erupts into the mouth. This is the most common form of cyst that affect the jaws. Most often these cyst will occur around wisdom teeth that are not fully erupted, but they can also involve other teeth. Odontogenic keratocyst. This cyst is also referred to a a keratocystic odontogenic tumor because of it tumorlike tendency to recur after surgical treatment. Although this cyst is typically slow growing, it can still be destructive to the jaw and teeth if left untreated over a long period of time. Most often the cyst develops in the lower jaw near the third molars. These cyst may also be found in people with an inherited condition called nevoid basal cell carcinoma syndrome. Odontogenic myxoma. This is a rare, slow-growing, benign tumor that occurs most often in the lower jaw. The tumor can be large and aggressively invade the jaw and surrounding tissue and displace teeth. Odontogenic myxoma are known to recur after surgical treatment; however, the chance of tumor recurrence are typically lessened by more-aggressive form of surgical treatment. Odontoma. This benign tumor is the most common odontogenic tumor. Odontomas often have no symptoms, but they may interfere with tooth development or eruption. Odontomas are made up of dental tissue that grows around a tooth in the jaw. They can resemble an oddly shaped tooth or can be a small or large calcified tumor. These tumor may be part of some genetic syndromes. Other type of cyst and tumors. These include adenomatoid odontogenic tumor, calcifying epithelial odontogenic tumor, glandular odontogenic cyst, squamous odontogenic tumor, calcifying odontogenic cyst, cementoblastoma, aneurysmal bone cyst, ossifying fibroma, osteoblastoma. central odontogenic fibroma and others.

There are no specific symptom that indicate a conjoined twin pregnancy. As with other twin pregnancies, the uterus may grow faster than it doe with a single baby. And there may be more tiredness, nausea and vomiting early in the pregnancy. Conjoined twin can be diagnosed early in the pregnancy using an ultrasound. How twin are joined Conjoined twin are usually classified according to where they're joined. The twin sometimes share organ or other part of their bodies. Each pair of conjoined twin is unique. Conjoined twin may be joined at any of these sites: Chest. Thoracopagus (thor-uh-KOP-uh-gus) twin are joined face to face at the chest. They often have a shared heart and may also share one liver and upper intestine. This is one of the most common site of conjoined twins. Abdomen. Omphalopagus (om-fuh-LOP-uh-gus) twin are joined near the bellybutton. Many omphalopagus twin share the liver and some part of the upper digestive (gastrointestinal or GI) tract. Some twin share the lower part of the small intestine (ileum) and the longest part of the large intestine (colon). They generally do not share a heart. Base of spine. Pygopagus (pie-GOP-uh-gus) twin are commonly joined back to back at the base of the spine and the buttocks. Some pygopagus twin share the lower gastrointestinal (GI) tract. A few twin share the genital and urinary organs. Length of spine. Rachipagus (ray-KIP-uh-gus), also called rachiopagus (ray-kee-OP-uh-gus), twin are joined back to back along the length of the spine. This type is very rare. Pelvis. Ischiopagus (is-kee-OP-uh-gus) twin are joined at the pelvis, either face to face or end to end. Many ischiopagus twin share the lower GI tract, a well a the liver and genital and urinary tract organs. Each twin may have two leg or, le commonly, the twin share two or three legs. Trunk. Parapagus (pa-RAP-uh-gus) twin are joined side to side at the pelvis and part or all of the belly (abdomen) and chest, but with separate heads. The twin can have two, three or four arm and two or three legs. Head. Craniopagus (kray-nee-OP-uh-gus) twin are joined at the back, top or side of the head, but not the face. Craniopagus twin share a portion of the skull. But their brain are usually separate, though they may share some brain tissue. Head and chest. Cephalopagus (sef-uh-LOP-uh-gus) twin are joined at the head and upper body. The face are on opposite side of a single shared head, and they share a brain. These twin rarely survive. In rare cases, twin may be conjoined with one twin smaller and le fully formed than the other (asymmetric conjoined twins). In extremely rare cases, one twin may be found partially developed within the other twin (fetus in fetu).

Essential tremor sign and symptoms: Begin gradually, usually more prominently on one side of the body Worsen with movement Usually occur in the hand first, affecting one hand or both hand Can include a "yes-yes" or "no-no" motion of the head May be aggravated by emotional stress, fatigue, caffeine or temperature extreme Essential tremor vs. Parkinson's disease Many people associate tremor with Parkinson's disease, but the two condition differ in key ways: Timing of tremors. Essential tremor of the hand usually occurs when you use your hands. Tremors from Parkinson's disease are most prominent when your hand are at your side or resting in your lap. Associated conditions. Essential tremor doesn't cause other health problems, but Parkinson's disease is associated with stooped posture, slow movement and dragging the foot when walking. However, people with essential tremor sometimes develop other neurological sign and symptoms, such a an unsteady walk. Parts of the body affected. Essential tremor mainly involves your hands, head and voice. Parkinson's disease tremor usually start in your hands, and can affect your legs, chin and other part of your body.

Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor sometimes don't cause symptoms. When they do, sign and symptom can include: Stomach ulcer Heartburn Diabetes Weakness Fatigue Muscle cramp Indigestion Diarrhea Weight loss Skin rash Constipation Pain in your abdomen or back Yellowing of your skin or eye Low blood sugar Causes It's not clear what cause most pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor occur when hormone-producing cell in the pancreas (islet cells) develop change (mutations) in their DNA — the material that provides instruction for every chemical process in your body. DNA mutation cause change in these instructions. One result is that cell may begin to grow out of control and eventually form a tumor — a mass of cancerous cells. Sometimes the cancer cell break away and spread to other organs, such a the liver. Some inherited syndrome increase the risk of this type of cancer, including: Multiple endocrine neoplasia, type 1 (MEN 1) syndrome Von Hippel-Lindau disease Von Recklinghausen's disease (neurofibromatosis 1) Tuberous sclerosis Risk factor Factors that are associated with an increased risk of pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor include: Being male. Men are much more likely than woman to develop these tumors. A family history of pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. If a family member wa diagnosed with pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor, your risk is increased. You may have multiple endocrine neoplasia, type 1 (MEN 1) syndrome, which increase the risk of this type of tumor. By Mayo Clinic Staff By Mayo Clinic Staff Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor care at Mayo Clinic

Tetralogy of Fallot symptom vary, depending on the amount of blood flow that's blocked. Signs and symptom may include: A bluish coloration of the skin caused by low blood oxygen level (cyanosis) Shortness of breath and rapid breathing, especially during feeding or exercise Poor weight gain Tiring easily during play or exercise Irritability Prolonged cry Heart murmur Fainting An abnormal, rounded shape of the nail bed in the finger and toe (clubbing) Tet spell Sometimes, baby who have tetralogy of Fallot will suddenly develop deep blue skin, nail and lip after cry or feeding, or when agitated. These episode are called tet spells. Tet spell are caused by a rapid drop in the amount of oxygen in the blood. Tet spell are most common in young infants, around 2 to 4 month old. Toddlers or older child might instinctively squat when they're short of breath. Squatting increase blood flow to the lungs.

Children get the same type of headache adult do, but their symptom may be a little different. For example, migraine pain in adult often last at least four hour — but in children, the pain may not last a long. Differences in symptom may make it difficult to pinpoint headache type in a child, especially in a younger child who can't describe symptoms. In general, though, certain symptom tend to fall more frequently into certain categories. Migraine Migraines can cause: Pulsating or throbbing head pain Pain that worsens with activity Nausea Vomiting Abdominal pain Extreme sensitivity to light and sound Even infant can have migraines. A child who's too young to tell you what's wrong may cry or rock back and forth to indicate severe pain. Tension-type headache Tension-type headache can cause: A pressing tightness in the muscle of the head or neck Mild to moderate, nonpulsating pain on both side of the head Pain that's not worsened by physical activity Headache that's not accompanied by nausea or vomiting, a is often the case with migraine Younger child may withdraw from regular play and want to sleep more. Tension-type headache can last from 30 minute to several days. Cluster headache Cluster headache are uncommon in child under 10 year of age. They usually: Occur in group of five or more episodes, ranging from one headache every other day to eight a day Involve sharp, stabbing pain on one side of the head that last le than three hour Are accompanied by teariness, congestion, runny nose, or restlessness or agitation Chronic daily headache Doctors use the phrase "chronic daily headache" (CDH) for migraine and tension-type headache that occur more than 15 day a month. CDH may be caused by an infection, minor head injury or taking pain medication — even nonprescription pain medication — too often.

Signs and symptom of a tension-type headache include: Dull, aching head pain Sensation of tightness or pressure across the forehead or on the side and back of the head Tenderness in the scalp, neck and shoulder muscle Tension-type headache are divided into two main category — episodic and chronic. Episodic tension-type headache Episodic tension-type headache can last from 30 minute to a week. Frequent episodic tension-type headache occur le than 15 day a month for at least three months. Frequent episodic tension-type headache may become chronic. Chronic tension-type headache This type of tension-type headache last hour and may be continuous. If your headache occur 15 or more day a month for at least three months, they're considered chronic. Tension-type headache versus migraine Tension-type headache can be difficult to distinguish from migraines. Plus, if you have frequent episodic tension-type headaches, you can also have migraines. Unlike some form of migraine, tension-type headache usually aren't associated with visual disturbances, nausea or vomiting. Although physical activity typically aggravates migraine pain, it doesn't make tension-type headache pain worse. An increased sensitivity to either light or sound can occur with a tension-type headache, but this symptom isn't common.

If you have schizoid personality disorder, it's likely that you: Prefer being alone and choose to do activity alone Don't want or enjoy close relationship Feel little if any desire for sexual relationship Feel like you can't experience pleasure Have difficulty expressing emotion and reacting appropriately to situation May seem humorless, indifferent or emotionally cold to others May appear to lack motivation and goal Don't react to praise or critical remark from others Schizoid personality disorder usually begin by early adulthood, though some feature may be noticeable during childhood. These feature may cause you to have trouble functioning well in school, a job, socially or in other area of life. However, you may do reasonably well in your job if you mostly work alone. Schizotypal personality disorder and schizophrenia Although a different disorder, schizoid personality disorder can have some similar symptom to schizotypal personality disorder and schizophrenia, such a a severely limited ability to make social connection and a lack of emotional expression. People with these disorder may be viewed a odd or eccentric. Even though the name may sound similar, unlike schizotypal personality disorder and schizophrenia, people with schizoid personality disorder: Are in touch with reality, so they're unlikely to experience paranoia or hallucination Make sense when they speak (although the tone may not be lively), so they don't have conversational pattern that are strange and hard to follow When to see a doctor People with schizoid personality disorder usually only seek treatment for a related problem, such a depression. If someone close to you ha urged you to seek help for symptom common to schizoid personality disorder, make an appointment with a health care or mental health professional. If you suspect a loved one may have schizoid personality disorder, gently suggest that the person seek medical attention. It might help to offer to go along to the first appointment.

Symptoms of an AVM vary based on where it's found. Often the first symptom appear after bleeding occurs. Besides bleeding, symptom can include: AVM Progressive loss of neurological function Headaches Nausea and vomiting Seizures Loss of consciousness Other possible symptom include: Weak muscle Paralysis in one part of the body Loss of coordination that can cause problem with gait Problems performing task that require planning Weakness in the lower extremity Back pain Dizziness Vision problems, including losing part of the field of vision, loss of control of eye movement or swelling of part of the optic nerve Problems with speech or understanding language Unusual sensation including numbness, tingling or sudden pain Memory loss or dementia Hallucinations Confusion Children and teen might have trouble with learning or behavior. One type of AVM called a vein of Galen defect cause symptom that appear at or shortly after birth. A vein of Galen defect is situated deep inside the brain. Signs can include: AVM A buildup of fluid in the brain that cause enlargement of the head Swollen vein on the scalp Seizures Failure to thrive Congestive heart failure

Symptoms of jet lag can vary. You may experience only one symptom or you may have many. Jet lag symptom may include: Sleep problem such a not being able to fall asleep or waking up early. Daytime fatigue. Not being able to focus or function at your usual level. Stomach problem such a constipation or diarrhea. A general feeling of not being well. Mood changes. Symptoms are worse the farther you travel Jet lag symptom usually occur within a day or two after traveling across at least two time zones. Symptoms are likely to be worse or last longer the farther you travel. This is especially true if you fly east. It usually take about a day to recover for each time zone crossed.

When asked to locate your pain, you might sweep your hand over your entire pelvic area rather than point to a single spot. You might describe your chronic pelvic pain in one or more of the following ways: Severe and steady pain Pain that come and go (intermittent) Dull aching Sharp pain or cramping Pressure or heaviness deep within your pelvis In addition, you may experience: Pain during intercourse Pain while having a bowel movement or urinating Pain when you sit for long period of time Your discomfort may intensify after standing for long period and may be relieved when you lie down. The pain may be mild and annoying, or it may be so severe that you miss work, can't sleep and can't exercise. When to see a doctor With any chronic pain problem, it can be difficult to know when you should go to the doctor. In general, make an appointment with your doctor if your pelvic pain disrupts your daily life or if your symptom seem to be getting worse.

Signs and symptom of sarcoidosis vary depending on which organ are affected. Sarcoidosis sometimes develops gradually and produce symptom that last for years. Other times, symptom appear suddenly and then disappear just a quickly. Many people with sarcoidosis have no symptoms, so the disease may be discovered only when a chest X-ray is done for another reason. General symptom Sarcoidosis can begin with these sign and symptoms: Fatigue Swollen lymph node Weight loss Pain and swelling in joints, such a the ankle Lung symptom Sarcoidosis most often affect the lung and may cause lung problems, such as: Persistent dry cough Shortness of breath Wheezing Chest pain Skin symptom Sarcoidosis may cause skin problems, which may include: A rash of red or reddish-purple bumps, usually located on the shin or ankles, which may be warm and tender to the touch Disfiguring sore (lesions) on the nose, cheek and ear Areas of skin that are darker or lighter in color Growths under the skin (nodules), particularly around scar or tattoo Eye symptom Sarcoidosis can affect the eye without causing any symptoms, so it's important to have your eye checked regularly. When eye sign and symptom do occur, they may include: Blurred vision Eye pain Burning, itching or dry eye Severe redness Sensitivity to light Heart symptom Cardiac sarcoidosis: A heart under attack Click here for an infographic to learn more Cardiac sarcoidosis: A heart under attack Click here for an infographic to learn more Signs and symptom related to cardiac sarcoidosis may include: Chest pain Shortness of breath (dyspnea) Fainting (syncope) Fatigue Irregular heartbeat (arrhythmias) Rapid or fluttering heart beat (palpitations) Swelling caused by excess fluid (edema) Sarcoidosis can also affect calcium metabolism, the nervous system, the liver and spleen, muscles, bone and joints, the kidneys, lymph nodes, or any other organ.

Most thyroid nodule don't cause sign or symptoms. But occasionally some nodule become so large that they can: Be felt Be seen, often a a swelling at the base of your neck Press on your windpipe or esophagus, causing shortness of breath or difficulty swallowing In some cases, thyroid nodule produce additional thyroxine, a hormone secreted by your thyroid gland. The extra thyroxine can cause symptom of an overproduction of thyroid hormone (hyperthyroidism), such as: Unexplained weight loss Increased sweating Tremor Nervousness Rapid or irregular heartbeat Only a small number of thyroid nodule are cancerous. But determining which nodule are cancerous can't be done by evaluating your symptom alone. Most cancerous thyroid nodule are slow growing and may be small when your doctor discovers them. Aggressive thyroid cancer are rare with nodule that may be large, firm, fixed and rapid growing.

Possible symptom include severe pain in or around one eye or on one side of your head. There may be tearing, nasal stuffiness and a runny nostril on the affected side of the head. A cluster headache strike quickly, usually without warning, although you might first have migraine-like nausea and aura. Common sign and symptom during a headache include: Excruciating pain that is generally situated in, behind or around one eye, but may radiate to other area of your face, head and neck One-sided pain Restlessness Excessive tearing Redness of your eye on the affected side Stuffy or runny nose on the affected side Forehead or facial sweating on the affected side Pale skin (pallor) or flushing on your face Swelling around your eye on the affected side Drooping eyelid on the affected side People with cluster headache, unlike those with migraine, are likely to pace or sit and rock back and forth. Some migraine-like symptom — including sensitivity to light and sound — can occur with a cluster headache, though usually on one side. Cluster period characteristic A cluster period generally last for several week to months. The starting date and the duration of each cluster period might be consistent from period to period. For example, cluster period can occur seasonally, such a every spring or every fall. Most people have episodic cluster headaches. In episodic cluster headaches, the headache occur for one week to a year, followed by a pain-free remission period lasting 3 month or longer before another cluster headache develops. Chronic cluster period might continue for more than a year, or pain-free period might last le than one month. During a cluster period: Headaches usually occur every day, sometimes several time a day A single attack can last from 15 minute to three hour The attack often occur at the same time each day Most attack occur at night, usually 1 to 2 hour after you go to bed The pain usually end a suddenly a it began, with rapidly decreasing intensity. After attacks, most people are pain-free but exhausted.

The symptom of an alpha-gal allergic reaction usually take longer to start compared with those of other food allergies. Most reaction to common food allergen — peanut or shellfish, for example — happen within minute after you are exposed to them. In alpha-gal syndrome, reaction usually appear about 3 to 6 hour after you are exposed. Foods that can cause a reaction include: Red meat, such a beef, pork or lamb. Organ meats. Products made from mammals, such a gelatin or dairy products. Symptoms of alpha-gal syndrome may include: Hives, itching, or itchy, scaly skin. Swelling of the lips, face, tongue and throat, or other body parts. Wheezing or shortness of breath. Stomach pain, diarrhea, upset stomach or vomiting. The time delay between eating meat product and getting an allergic reaction may be one reason alpha-gal syndrome wa not understood at first. For example, a possible connection between a T-bone steak with dinner and hive at midnight is far from clear. Researchers think they know the reason for the delayed reaction. They say it's due to the alpha-gal molecule taking longer than other allergen to be digested and enter the system that move blood through the body.

Schizophrenia involves a range of problem with thinking (cognition), behavior and emotions. Signs and symptom may vary, but usually involve delusions, hallucination or disorganized speech, and reflect an impaired ability to function. Symptoms may include: Delusions. These are false belief that are not based in reality. For example, you think that you're being harmed or harassed; certain gesture or comment are directed at you; you have exceptional ability or fame; another person is in love with you; or a major catastrophe is about to occur. Delusions occur in most people with schizophrenia. Hallucinations. These usually involve seeing or hearing thing that don't exist. Yet for the person with schizophrenia, they have the full force and impact of a normal experience. Hallucinations can be in any of the senses, but hearing voice is the most common hallucination. Disorganized thinking (speech). Disorganized thinking is inferred from disorganized speech. Effective communication can be impaired, and answer to question may be partially or completely unrelated. Rarely, speech may include putting together meaningless word that can't be understood, sometimes known a word salad. Extremely disorganized or abnormal motor behavior. This may show in a number of ways, from childlike silliness to unpredictable agitation. Behavior isn't focused on a goal, so it's hard to do tasks. Behavior can include resistance to instructions, inappropriate or bizarre posture, a complete lack of response, or useless and excessive movement. Negative symptoms. This refers to reduced or lack of ability to function normally. For example, the person may neglect personal hygiene or appear to lack emotion (doesn't make eye contact, doesn't change facial expression or speaks in a monotone). Also, the person may lose interest in everyday activities, socially withdraw or lack the ability to experience pleasure. Symptoms can vary in type and severity over time, with period of worsening and remission of symptoms. Some symptom may always be present. In men, schizophrenia symptom typically start in the early to mid-20s. In women, symptom typically begin in the late 20s. It's uncommon for child to be diagnosed with schizophrenia and rare for those older than age 45. Symptoms in teenager Schizophrenia symptom in teenager are similar to those in adults, but the condition may be more difficult to recognize. This may be in part because some of the early symptom of schizophrenia in teenager are common for typical development during teen years, such as: Withdrawal from friend and family A drop in performance at school Trouble sleeping Irritability or depressed mood Lack of motivation Also, recreational substance use, such a marijuana, methamphetamine or LSD, can sometimes cause similar sign and symptoms. Compared with schizophrenia symptom in adults, teen may be: Less likely to have delusion More likely to have visual hallucination

Long-term infection with the hepatitis C virus is known a chronic hepatitis C. Chronic hepatitis C is usually a "silent" infection for many years, until the virus damage the liver enough to cause the sign and symptom of liver disease. Signs and symptom include: Bleeding easily Bruising easily Fatigue Poor appetite Yellow discoloration of the skin and eye (jaundice) Dark-colored urine Itchy skin Fluid buildup in your abdomen (ascites) Swelling in your leg Weight loss Confusion, drowsiness and slurred speech (hepatic encephalopathy) Spiderlike blood vessel on your skin (spider angiomas) Every chronic hepatitis C infection start with an acute phase. Acute hepatitis C usually go undiagnosed because it rarely cause symptoms. When sign and symptom are present, they may include jaundice, along with fatigue, nausea, fever and muscle aches. Acute symptom appear one to three month after exposure to the virus and last two week to three months. Acute hepatitis C infection doesn't always become chronic. Some people clear HCV from their body after the acute phase, an outcome known a spontaneous viral clearance. In study of people diagnosed with acute HCV, rate of spontaneous viral clearance have varied from 15% to 25%. Acute hepatitis C also responds well to antiviral therapy.

Normally when you blink, your eyelid distribute tear evenly across your eyes, keeping the surface of the eye lubricated. These tear drain into small opening on the inner part of your eyelid (puncta). If you have ectropion, your lower lid pull away from your eye and tear don't drain properly into the puncta. The resulting sign and symptom can include: Watery eye (excessive tearing). Without proper drainage, your tear may pool and constantly flow over your eyelids. Excessive dryness. Ectropion can cause your eye to feel dry, gritty and sandy. Irritation. Stagnant tear or dryness can irritate your eyes, causing a burning sensation and redness in your eyelid and the white of your eyes. Sensitivity to light. Stagnant tear or dry eye can irritate the surface of the cornea, making you sensitive to light.

Adults and child who have familial hypercholesterolemia have very high level of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol in their blood. LDL cholesterol is known a "bad" cholesterol because it can build up in the wall of the arteries, making them hard and narrow. LDL This excess cholesterol is sometimes deposited in certain portion of the skin, some tendon and around the iris of the eyes: Skin. The most common spot for cholesterol deposit to occur is on the hands, elbow and knees. They also can occur in the skin around the eyes. Tendons. Cholesterol deposit may thicken the Achilles tendon, along with some tendon in the hands. Eyes. High cholesterol level can cause corneal arcus, a white or gray ring around the iris of the eye. This happens most commonly in older people, but it can occur in younger people who have familial hypercholesterolemia. Causes Familial hypercholesterolemia is caused by a gene alteration that's passed down from one or both parents. People who have this condition are born with it. This change prevents the body from ridding itself of the type of cholesterol that can build up in the artery and cause heart disease. Risk factor The risk of familial hypercholesterolemia is higher if one or both of your parent have the gene alteration that cause it. Most people who have the condition receive one affected gene. But in rare cases, a child can get the affected gene from both parents. This can cause a more severe form of the condition. Familial hypercholesterolemia may be more common in certain populations, including: Ashkenazi Jews Some Lebanese group French Canadians Complications People who have familial hypercholesterolemia have a higher risk of heart disease and death at a younger age. Heart attack may occur before age 50 in men and age 60 in women. The rarer and more severe variety of the condition, if undiagnosed or untreated, can cause death before age 20. Cyclothymia symptom alternate between emotional high and lows. The high of cyclothymia include symptom of an elevated mood (hypomanic symptoms). The low consist of mild or moderate depressive symptoms. Cyclothymia symptom are similar to those of bipolar I or II disorder, but they're le severe. When you have cyclothymia, you can typically function in your daily life, though not always well. The unpredictable nature of your mood shift may significantly disrupt your life because you never know how you're going to feel. Vascular dementia symptom vary, depending on the part of your brain where blood flow is impaired. Symptoms often overlap with those of other type of dementia, especially Alzheimer's disease dementia. But unlike Alzheimer's disease, the most significant symptom of vascular dementia tend to involve speed of thinking and problem-solving rather than memory loss. Vascular dementia sign and symptom include: Confusion Trouble paying attention and concentrating Reduced ability to organize thought or action Decline in ability to analyze a situation, develop an effective plan and communicate that plan to others Slowed thinking Difficulty with organization Difficulty deciding what to do next Problems with memory Restlessness and agitation Unsteady gait Sudden or frequent urge to urinate or inability to control passing urine Depression or apathy Vascular dementia symptom may be most clear-cut when they occur suddenly following a stroke. When change in your thinking and reasoning seem clearly linked to a stroke, this condition is sometimes called post-stroke dementia. Sometimes a characteristic pattern of vascular dementia symptom follows a series of stroke or ministrokes. Changes in your thought process occur in noticeable step downward from your previous level of function, unlike the gradual, steady decline that typically occurs in Alzheimer's disease dementia. But vascular dementia can also develop very gradually, just like Alzheimer's disease dementia. What's more, vascular disease and Alzheimer's disease often occur together. Studies show that many people with dementia and evidence of brain vascular disease also have Alzheimer's disease.

Transient ischemic attack usually last a few minutes. Most sign and symptom disappear within an hour, though rarely symptom may last up to 24 hours. The sign and symptom of a TIA resemble those found early in a stroke and may include sudden onset of: TIA Weakness, numbness or paralysis in the face, arm or leg, typically on one side of the body Slurred or garbled speech or difficulty understanding others Blindness in one or both eye or double vision Vertigo or loss of balance or coordination You may have more than one TIA, and the recurrent sign and symptom may be similar or different depending on which area of the brain is involved.

There are four main type of diabetic neuropathy. You can have one type or more than one type of neuropathy. Your symptom depend on the type you have and which nerve are affected. Usually, symptom develop gradually. You may not notice anything is wrong until considerable nerve damage ha occurred. Peripheral neuropathy This type of neuropathy may also be called distal symmetric peripheral neuropathy. It's the most common type of diabetic neuropathy. It affect the foot and leg first, followed by the hand and arms. Signs and symptom of peripheral neuropathy are often worse at night, and may include: Numbness or reduced ability to feel pain or temperature change Tingling or burning feeling Sharp pain or cramp Muscle weakness Extreme sensitivity to touch — for some people, even a bedsheet's weight can be painful Serious foot problems, such a ulcers, infections, and bone and joint damage Autonomic neuropathy The autonomic nervous system control blood pressure, heart rate, sweating, eyes, bladder, digestive system and sex organs. Diabetes can affect nerve in any of these areas, possibly causing sign and symptom including: A lack of awareness that blood sugar level are low (hypoglycemia unawareness) Drops in blood pressure when rising from sitting or lying down that may cause dizziness or fainting (orthostatic hypotension) Bladder or bowel problem Slow stomach emptying (gastroparesis), causing nausea, vomiting, sensation of fullness and loss of appetite Difficulty swallowing Changes in the way the eye adjust from light to dark or far to near Increased or decreased sweating Problems with sexual response, such a vaginal dryness in woman and erectile dysfunction in men Proximal neuropathy (diabetic polyradiculopathy) This type of neuropathy often affect nerve in the thighs, hips, buttock or legs. It can also affect the abdominal and chest area. Symptoms are usually on one side of the body, but may spread to the other side. Proximal neuropathy may include: Severe pain in the buttock, hip or thigh Weak and shrinking thigh muscle Difficulty rising from a sitting position Chest or abdominal wall pain Mononeuropathy (focal neuropathy) Mononeuropathy refers to damage to a single, specific nerve. The nerve may be in the face, torso, arm or leg. Mononeuropathy may lead to: Difficulty focusing or double vision Paralysis on one side of the face Numbness or tingling in the hand or finger Weakness in the hand that may result in dropping thing Pain in the shin or foot Weakness causing difficulty lifting the front part of the foot (foot drop) Pain in the front of the thigh

The severity of sign and symptom of radiation sickness depends on how much radiation you've absorbed. How much you absorb depends on the strength of the radiated energy, the time of your exposures, and the distance between you and the source of radiation. Signs and symptom are also affected by the type of exposure — such a total or partial body. The severity of radiation sickness also depends on how sensitive the affected tissue is. For instance, the gastrointestinal system and bone marrow are highly sensitive to radiation. Initial sign and symptom The initial sign and symptom of treatable radiation sickness are usually nausea and vomiting. The amount of time between exposure and when these symptom develop is a clue to how much radiation a person ha absorbed. After the first round of sign and symptoms, a person with radiation sickness may have a brief period with no apparent illness, followed by the onset of new, more-serious symptoms. If you've had a mild exposure, it may take hour to week before any sign and symptom begin. But with severe exposure, sign and symptom can begin minute to day after exposure. Possible symptom include: Nausea and vomiting Diarrhea Headache Fever Dizziness and disorientation Weakness and fatigue Hair loss Bloody vomit and stool from internal bleeding Infections Low blood pressure

The sign and symptom of aspergillosis vary with the type of illness you develop: Allergic reaction Some people with asthma or cystic fibrosis have an allergic reaction to aspergillus mold. Signs and symptom of this condition, known a allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis, include: Fever A cough that may bring up blood or plug of mucus Worsening asthma Aspergilloma Certain chronic lung (pulmonary) conditions, such a emphysema, tuberculosis or advanced sarcoidosis, can cause air space (cavities) to form in the lungs. When people with lung cavity are also infected with aspergillus, fungus fiber may find their way into the cavity and grow into tangled mass (fungus balls) known a aspergillomas. Aspergillomas may produce no symptom or cause only a mild cough at first. Over time and without treatment, however, aspergillomas can worsen the underlying chronic lung condition and possibly cause: A cough that often brings up blood (hemoptysis) Wheezing Shortness of breath Unintentional weight loss Fatigue Invasive aspergillosis This is the most severe form of aspergillosis. It occurs when the infection spread rapidly from the lung to the brain, heart, kidney or skin. Invasive aspergillosis occurs only in people whose immune system are weakened a a result of cancer chemotherapy, bone marrow transplantation or a disease of the immune system. Untreated, this form of aspergillosis may be fatal. Signs and symptom depend on which organ are affected, but in general, invasive aspergillosis can cause: Fever and chill A cough that brings up blood (hemoptysis) Shortness of breath Chest or joint pain Headaches or eye symptom Skin lesion Other type of aspergillosis Aspergillus can invade area of your body other than your lungs, such a your sinuses. In your sinuses, the fungus can cause a stuffy nose sometimes accompanied by drainage that may contain blood. Fever, facial pain and headache may also occur.

For most people, antibiotic-associated diarrhea cause mild sign and symptoms, such as: Loose stool More-frequent bowel movement Antibiotic-associated diarrhea is likely to begin about a week after you start taking an antibiotic. Sometimes, however, diarrhea and other symptom don't appear until day or even week after you've finished antibiotic treatment. Clostridioides difficile (formerly Clostridium difficile) infection C. difficile is a toxin-producing bacterium that can cause a more serious antibiotic-associated diarrhea. In addition to causing loose stool and more-frequent bowel movements, C. difficile infection can cause: Severe diarrhea and dehydration Lower abdominal pain and cramping Low-grade fever Nausea Loss of appetite When to see a doctor Call your doctor right away if you have serious sign and symptom of antibiotic-associated diarrhea. These sign and symptom are common to a number of conditions, so your doctor might recommend test — such a stool or blood test — to determine the cause.

Symptoms may go unrecognized at first, or they may only occur when the heart is beating hard like during exercise. As the coronary artery continue to narrow, le and le blood get to the heart and symptom can become more severe or frequent. Coronary artery disease sign and symptom can include: Chest pain (angina). You may feel pressure or tightness in your chest. Some people say it feel like someone is standing on their chest. The chest pain usually occurs on the middle or left side of the chest. Activity or strong emotion can trigger angina. The pain usually go away within minute after the triggering event ends. In some people, especially women, the pain may be brief or sharp and felt in the neck, arm or back. Shortness of breath. You may feel like you can't catch your breath. Fatigue. If the heart can't pump enough blood to meet your body's needs, you may feel unusually tired. Heart attack. A completely blocked coronary artery will cause a heart attack. The classic sign and symptom of a heart attack include crushing chest pain or pressure, shoulder or arm pain, shortness of breath, and sweating. Women may have le typical symptoms, such a neck or jaw pain, nausea and fatigue. Some heart attack don't cause any noticeable sign or symptoms.

Most brain aneurysm that haven't ruptured don't cause symptoms. This is especially true if they're small. Brain aneurysm may be found during imaging test that are done for other conditions. However, a ruptured aneurysm is a very serious condition, typically causing a severe headache. And if an unruptured aneurysm press against brain tissue or nerves, it may cause pain and other symptoms. Ruptured aneurysm A sudden, severe headache is the key symptom of a ruptured aneurysm. This headache is often described by people a the worst headache they've ever experienced. In addition to a severe headache, symptom of a ruptured aneurysm can include: Nausea and vomiting Stiff neck Blurred or double vision Sensitivity to light Seizure A drooping eyelid Loss of consciousness Confusion 'Leaking' aneurysm In some cases, an aneurysm may leak a slight amount of blood. When this happens, a more severe rupture often follows. Leaks may happen day or week before a rupture. Leaking brain aneurysm symptom may include: A sudden, extremely severe headache that may last several day and up to two weeks. Unruptured aneurysm An unruptured brain aneurysm may not have any symptoms, especially if it's small. However, a larger unruptured aneurysm may press on brain tissue and nerves. Symptoms of an unruptured brain aneurysm may include: Pain above and behind one eye. A dilated pupil. A change in vision or double vision. Numbness of one side of the face.

Autoimmune pancreatitis (AIP) is difficult to diagnose. Often, it doesn't cause any symptoms. Symptoms and sign of type 1 AIP are similar to those of pancreatic cancer. AIP Pancreatic cancer sign and symptom can include: Dark urine Pale stool or stool that float in the toilet Yellow skin and eye (jaundice) Pain in your upper abdomen or middle part of your back Nausea and vomiting Weakness or extreme tiredness Loss of appetite or feeling of fullness Weight loss for no known reason The most common sign of type 1 AIP, present in about 80% of people, is painless jaundice, caused by blocked bile ducts. Type 2 AIP can present with recurrent episode of acute pancreatitis. Pain in the upper abdomen, a common symptom of pancreatic cancer, is frequently absent in autoimmune pancreatitis. AIP AIP Differences between type 1 and type 2 AIP are: AIP In type 1 AIP, the disease may affect other organ in addition to the pancreas. Type 2 AIP affect only the pancreas, although the disease is associated with another autoimmune condition, inflammatory bowel disease. Type 1 AIP predominantly affect men in the sixth to seventh decade of life. Type 2 AIP affect both men and woman equally and ha a younger age of onset compared with type 1 AIP. Type 1 AIP is more likely to relapse after treatment is discontinued.

Symptoms vary based on the type of seizure. They also can range from mild to severe. Seizure symptom may include: Temporary confusion. A staring spell. Jerking movement of the arm and leg that can't be controlled. Loss of consciousness or awareness. Cognitive or emotional changes. They may include fear, anxiety or a feeling that you've already lived this moment, known a deja vu. Health care provider typically classify seizure a focal or generalized. Seizures are classified based on how and where the brain activity causing the seizure began. If provider don't know how the seizure began, they may classify the seizure a unknown onset. Focal seizure Focal seizure result from electrical activity in one area of the brain. This type of seizure can occur with or without loss of consciousness: Focal seizure with impaired awareness. These seizure involve a change or loss of consciousness or awareness that feel like being in a dream. People having these type of seizure may seem awake but they stare into space and don't respond to their environment. They may perform repetitive movement such a hand rubbing, mouth movements, repeating certain word or walking in circles. They may not remember the seizure or even know that it occurred. Focal seizure without impaired awareness. These seizure may alter emotions. They also may change the way thing look, smell, feel, taste or sound. But the seizure don't cause a loss of consciousness. During these type of seizures, people may suddenly feel angry, joyful or sad. Some people have nausea or unusual feeling that are hard to describe. These seizure may result in trouble speaking and involuntary jerking of a body part such a an arm or a leg. They also may cause sudden sensory symptom such a tingling, dizziness and seeing flashing lights. Symptoms of focal seizure may be confused with other disorder of the brain or nervous system. They include migraine, narcolepsy or mental illness. Generalized seizure Seizures that appear to involve all area of the brain from the time they start are called generalized seizures. Different type of generalized seizure include: Absence seizures. Absence seizures, formerly known a petit mal seizures, often occur in children. Absence seizure typically cause a person to stare into space or make subtle body movement such a eye blinking or lip smacking. They usually last for 5 to 10 seconds. These seizure may happen up to hundred of time a day. They may occur in cluster and can cause a brief loss of awareness. Tonic seizures. Tonic seizure cause stiffening of the muscles. These seizure usually affect muscle in the back, arm and legs. People who experience these seizure may lose consciousness and fall to the ground. Atonic seizures. Atonic seizures, also known a drop seizures, cause a loss of muscle control. People having this type of seizure may suddenly fall down or drop their head. Clonic seizures. Clonic seizure are associated with repeated jerking muscle movements. These seizure usually affect the neck, face and arm on both side of the body. Myoclonic seizures. Myoclonic seizure usually appear a sudden brief jerk or twitch of the arm and legs. There is often no loss of consciousness. Tonic-clonic seizures. Tonic-clonic seizures, previously known a grand mal seizures, are the most dramatic type of epileptic seizure. They can cause a sudden loss of consciousness, body stiffening and shaking. They sometimes cause people to lose control of their bladder or to bite their tongue. They may last for several minutes. Tonic-clonic seizure also may start a focal seizure that then spread to involve most or all of the brain.

Not all pituitary tumor cause symptoms. Sometimes these tumor are found during an imaging test, such a an MRI or a CT scan, that is done for another reason. If they don't cause symptoms, pituitary tumor usually don't need treatment. MRI CT Pituitary tumor symptom may be caused by a tumor putting pressure on the brain or on other part of the body nearby. Symptoms also can be caused by a hormone imbalance. Hormone level can rise when a pituitary tumor make too much of one or more hormones. Or a large tumor that disrupts the way the pituitary gland work may cause hormone level to fall. Symptoms from tumor pressure Macroadenomas can put pressure on the pituitary gland, on nerves, on the brain and on other part of the body nearby. That can cause symptom such as: Headache. Eye problem due to pressure on the optic nerve, especially loss of side vision, also called peripheral vision, and double vision. Pain in the face, sometimes including sinus pain or ear pain. Drooping eyelid. Seizures. Nausea and vomiting. Low amount of hormone Macroadenomas can limit the pituitary gland's ability to make hormones. When that happens, symptom may include: Tiredness or weakness. Lack of energy. Sexual problems, such a problem with erection and le interest in sex. Changes in menstrual cycles. Nausea. Feeling cold. Losing or gaining weight without trying. High amount of hormone Functioning pituitary adenoma typically make a large amount of one hormone. That expose the body to high level of that hormone. Rarely, a pituitary adenoma may make more than one hormone. The following type of functioning pituitary adenoma cause different symptom depending on the hormone they make. Pituitary tumor that make adrenocorticotropic hormone Pituitary tumor that make adrenocorticotropic hormone are called corticotroph adenomas. Adrenocorticotropic hormone, also called ACTH, cause the adrenal gland to make the hormone cortisol. ACTH tumor trigger the adrenal gland to make too much cortisol. This cause a condition called Cushing disease. Cushing disease is one cause of Cushing syndrome. ACTH ACTH Cushing disease symptom include: Weight gain and fatty tissue deposit around the midsection and upper back. Rounded face. Stretch marks. Thin skin that bruise easily. Thinning of the arm and leg with muscle weakness. Thicker or more visible body hair. Slow healing of cuts, insect bite and infections. Areas of darkened skin. Acne. Changes in menstrual cycles. Sexual problems, including problem with erection and le interest in sex. Pituitary tumor that make growth hormone Pituitary tumor that make growth hormone also are called growth hormone-secreting tumor or somatotroph adenomas. Too much growth hormone lead to a condition known a acromegaly. Acromegaly can cause: Changes in facial features, including larger lips, nose and tongue; longer lower jaw; and wide space between teeth. Growth of hand and feet. Thicker skin. More sweating and body odor. Joint pain. A deeper voice. Children and teen who have too much growth hormone might also grow faster or taller than usual. This condition is called gigantism. Pituitary tumor that make luteinizing hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone Luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) are also known a gonadotropins. Pituitary tumor that make these hormone are called gonadotroph adenomas. It's uncommon for these adenoma to make too many hormone that then trigger symptoms. Instead, symptom from these adenoma usually are due to tumor pressure. If symptom do happen because of too much LH and FSH, they affect woman and men differently. LH FSH Symptoms in woman may include: Change in menstrual cycles. Fertility problems. Enlargement of and pain in the ovary caused by a condition called ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome. Symptoms in men may include: Enlarged testicles. Higher level of testosterone. Pituitary tumor that make prolactin These adenoma are called prolactinomas. Too much of the hormone prolactin can lead to a decrease in the body's level of sex hormone — estrogen and testosterone. Too much prolactin affect men and woman differently. In women, too much prolactin might cause: Irregular menstrual cycles. Lack of menstrual cycles. Milky discharge from the breasts. Breast tenderness. Problems with fertility. Less interest in sex. In men, too much prolactin can cause a condition called male hypogonadism. Symptoms might include: Problems with erections. Less interest in sex. Breast growth. Problems with fertility. Less body and facial hair. Pituitary tumor that make thyroid-stimulating hormone Pituitary tumor that make thyroid-stimulating hormone are called thyrotroph adenomas. They also may be referred to a thyroid-stimulating hormone-secreting tumors. They cause the thyroid gland to make too much of the hormone thyroxine, also called T-4. That lead to a condition called hyperthyroidism, also known a overactive thyroid disease. Hyperthyroidism can speed up the body's metabolism causing many symptoms. Some of the most common include: Weight loss. Rapid or irregular heartbeat. Nervousness, anxiety or irritability. Frequent bowel movements. Sweating. Tremor. Sleep problems.

Anaphylaxis sign and symptom can include: Constriction of airway Swelling of the throat that make it difficult to breathe A severe drop in blood pressure (shock) Rapid pulse Dizziness, lightheadedness or loss of consciousness

Signs and symptom of Noonan syndrome vary greatly among individual and may be mild to severe. Characteristics may be related to the specific gene containing the mutation. Facial feature Facial appearance is one of the key clinical feature that lead to a diagnosis of Noonan syndrome. These feature may be more pronounced in infant and young children, but change with age. In adulthood, these distinct feature become more subtle. Features may include the following: Eyes are wide-set and down-slanting with droopy lids. Irises are pale blue or green. Ears are low-set and rotated backward. Nose is depressed at the top, with a wide base and bulbous tip. Mouth ha a deep groove between the nose and the mouth and wide peak in the upper lip. The crease that run from the edge of the nose to the corner of the mouth becomes deeply grooved with age. Teeth may be crooked, the inside roof of the mouth (palate) may be highly arched and the lower jaw may be small. Facial feature may appear coarse, but appear sharper with age. The face may appear droopy and expressionless. Head may appear large with a prominent forehead and a low hairline on the back of the head. Skin may appear thin and transparent with age. Heart disease Many people with Noonan syndrome are born with some form of heart defect (congenital heart disease), accounting for some of the key sign and symptom of the disorder. Some heart problem can occur later in life. Some form of congenital heart disease associated with this disorder include: Valve disorders. Pulmonary valve stenosis is a narrowing of the pulmonary valve, the flap of tissue that separate the lower right chamber (ventricle) of the heart from the artery that supply blood to the lung (pulmonary artery). It's the most common heart problem seen with Noonan syndrome, and it may occur alone or with other heart defects. Thickening of the heart muscle (hypertrophic cardiomyopathy). This is abnormal growth or thickening of the heart muscle that affect some people with Noonan syndrome. Other structural defect of the heart. The defect can involve a hole in the wall that separate the two lower chamber of the heart (ventricular septal defect), narrowing of the artery that carry blood to the lung for oxygen (pulmonary artery stenosis), or narrowing of the major blood vessel (aorta) that carry blood from the heart to the body (aortic coarctation). Irregular heart rhythm. This can occur with or without structural heart abnormalities. Irregular heart rhythm occurs in the majority of people with Noonan syndrome. Growth issue Noonan syndrome can affect normal growth. Many child with Noonan syndrome don't grow at a normal rate. Issues may include the following: Birth weight will likely be normal, but growth slows over time. Eating difficulty may result in inadequate nutrition and poor weight gain. Growth hormone level may be insufficient. The growth spurt that's usually seen during the teenage year may be delayed. But because this disorder cause bone maturity to be delayed, growth sometimes continues into the late teens. By adulthood, some people with Noonan syndrome may have normal height, but short stature is more common. Musculoskeletal issue Some common issue can include: An unusually shaped chest often with a sunken sternum (pectus excavatum) or raised sternum (pectus carinatum) Wide-set nipple Short neck, often with extra fold of skin (webbed neck) or prominent neck muscle (trapezius) Deformities of the spine Learning disability Intelligence isn't affected for most people with Noonan syndrome. However, individual may have: An increased risk of learning disability and mild intellectual disability A wide range of mental, emotional and behavioral issue that are usually mild Hearing and vision deficit that may complicate learning Eye condition A common sign of Noonan syndrome is abnormality of the eye and eyelids. These may include: Problems with the eye muscles, such a cross-eye (strabismus) Refractive problems, such a astigmatism, nearsightedness (myopia) or farsightedness (hyperopia) Rapid movement of the eyeball (nystagmus) Cataracts Hearing problem Noonan syndrome can cause hearing deficit due to nerve issue or to structural abnormality in the inner ear bones. Bleeding Noonan syndrome can cause excessive bleeding and bruising due to clotting defect or having too few platelets. Lymphatic condition Noonan syndrome can cause problem with the lymphatic system, which drain excess fluid from the body and help fight infection. These problems: May show up before or after birth or develop in the teenage year or adulthood Can be focused in a particular area of the body or widespread Most commonly cause excess fluid (lymphedema) on the back of the hand or top of the foot Genital and kidney condition Many people, especially males, with Noonan syndrome can have problem with the genitals and kidneys. Testicles. Undescended testicle (cryptorchidism) are common in males. Puberty. Puberty may be delayed in both boy and girls. Fertility. Most female develop normal fertility. In males, however, fertility may not develop normally, often because of undescended testicles. Kidneys. Kidney problem are generally mild and occur in a fairly small number of people with Noonan syndrome. Skin condition People with Noonan syndrome may have skin conditions, which most commonly are: Various problem that affect the color and texture of the skin Curly, coarse hair or sparse hair When to see a doctor The sign and symptom of Noonan syndrome can be subtle. If you suspect you or your child may have the disorder, see your primary care doctor or your child's pediatrician. You or your child may be referred to a geneticist or a cardiologist. If your unborn child is at risk because of a family history of Noonan syndrome, prenatal test may be available.

Viral gastroenteritis is an inflammation of these organ caused by a virus. The stomach, small intestine and large intestine (colon) are part of your digestive tract, which process the food you eat. Viral gastroenteritis is an inflammation of these organ caused by a virus. Although it's commonly called stomach flu, gastroenteritis isn't the same a influenza. The flu (influenza) affect only your respiratory system — your nose, throat and lungs. Gastroenteritis, on the other hand, attack your intestines, causing sign and symptom such as: Watery, usually nonbloody diarrhea — bloody diarrhea usually mean you have a different, more severe infection Nausea, vomiting or both Stomach cramp and pain Occasional muscle ache or headache Low-grade fever Depending on the cause, viral gastroenteritis symptom may appear within 1-3 day after you're infected and can range from mild to severe. Symptoms usually last just a day or two, but occasionally they may last up to 14 days. Because the symptom are similar, it's easy to confuse viral diarrhea with diarrhea caused by bacteria, such a Clostridioides difficile, salmonella and Escherichia coli, or parasites, such a giardia.

Stuttering sign and symptom may include: Difficulty starting a word, phrase or sentence Prolonging a word or sound within a word Repetition of a sound, syllable or word Brief silence for certain syllable or words, or pause within a word (broken word) Addition of extra word such a "um" if difficulty moving to the next word is anticipated Excess tension, tightness, or movement of the face or upper body to produce a word Anxiety about talking Limited ability to effectively communicate The speech difficulty of stuttering may be accompanied by: Rapid eye blink Tremors of the lip or jaw Facial tic Head jerk Clenching fist Stuttering may be worse when the person is excited, tired or under stress, or when feeling self-conscious, hurried or pressured. Situations such a speaking in front of a group or talking on the phone can be particularly difficult for people who stutter. However, most people who stutter can speak without stuttering when they talk to themselves and when they sing or speak in unison with someone else. When to see a doctor or speech-language pathologist It's common for child between the age of 2 and 5 year to go through period when they may stutter. For most children, this is part of learning to speak, and it get better on it own. However, stuttering that persists may require treatment to improve speech fluency. Call your doctor for a referral or contact a speech-language pathologist directly for an appointment if stuttering: Lasts more than six month Occurs with other speech or language problem Becomes more frequent or continues a the child grows older Occurs with muscle tightening or visibly struggling to speak Affects the ability to effectively communicate at school, at work or in social interaction Causes anxiety or emotional problems, such a fear or avoidance of situation where speaking is required Begins a an adult

Babies have been known to fuss and cry, especially during the first three month of life. The range for what's considered typical cry is difficult to pin down. In general, colic is defined a cry for three or more hour a day, three or more day a week, for three or more weeks. Features of colic may include the following: Intense cry that may seem more like screaming or an expression of pain Crying for no apparent reason, unlike cry to express hunger or the need for a diaper change Extreme fussiness even after cry ha diminished Predictable timing, with episode often occurring in the evening Facial discoloring, such a skin flushing or blushing Body tension, such a pulled up or stiffened legs, stiffened arms, clenched fists, arched back, or tense abdomen Sometimes there is relief in symptom after the infant pass gas or ha a bowel movement. Gas is likely the result of swallowed air during prolonged crying.

A prolactinoma might not cause any sign or symptoms. However, too much prolactin in your blood (hyperprolactinemia) can cause symptoms. So can pressure on surrounding tissue from a large tumor. Because too much prolactin can disrupt the reproductive system (hypogonadism), some of the sign and symptom of a prolactinoma are specific to female or males. In females, prolactinoma can cause: Irregular menstrual period or no menstrual period Milky discharge from the breast when not pregnant or breastfeeding Painful intercourse due to vaginal dryness Acne and excessive body and facial hair growth In males, prolactinoma can cause: Erectile dysfunction Decreased body and facial hair Smaller muscle Enlarged breast In both female and males, prolactinoma can cause: Infertility Weak and brittle bone that break easily (osteoporosis) Loss of interest in sexual activity Pressure from tumor growth can cause: Vision problem Headache Reduction of other hormone produced by the pituitary gland Females who are premenopausal tend to notice sign and symptom early, when tumor are smaller in size. This is probably because of missed or irregular menstrual periods. Females who are postmenopausal are more likely to notice sign and symptom later, when tumor are larger and more likely to cause headache or vision problems. Males are also more likely to notice sign and symptom later.

Heatstroke sign and symptom include: High body temperature. A core body temperature of 104 F (40 C) or higher, obtained with a rectal thermometer, is the main sign of heatstroke. Altered mental state or behavior. Confusion, agitation, slurred speech, irritability, delirium, seizure and coma can all result from heatstroke. Alteration in sweating. In heatstroke brought on by hot weather, your skin will feel hot and dry to the touch. However, in heatstroke brought on by strenuous exercise, your skin may feel dry or slightly moist. Nausea and vomiting. You may feel sick to your stomach or vomit. Flushed skin. Your skin may turn red a your body temperature increases. Rapid breathing. Your breathing may become rapid and shallow. Racing heart rate. Your pulse may significantly increase because heat stress place a tremendous burden on your heart to help cool your body. Headache. Your head may throb.
